Everything is a commodity. Time and water are both actually commodities, and artwork falls into the category governing the latter. An artist first capitalizes on his or her skill; when they become so popular that demand exceeds what they can feasibly produce within a reasonable span of time, that artist's mere ATTENTION becomes a commodity. In the Renaissance, ARTISTS were a commodity up 'til they died, at which point their individual works, outliving them, simply increase in value every year they're gone, especially as more and more people come to cherish them. We live in an age when there are so many artists alive right now and many, many more people wanting to acquire their time. There might seem to be an infinite number of them, so rather than become purely objectified and commoditized themselves, they can simply remain within their hubs make a living selling their time rather than their work.
